   ! Tickets (BUTTON) Menu

La Messe là-bas

   by Paul Claudel
   Design and interpretation Didier Sandre

   Studio
   April October 2020
   Available soon

   © c-album

   Studio

   La Messe là-bas

   2020-04-01 00:00:00 2020-10-31 00:00:00
   Available soon

   This text was composed during the First World War in Rio de Janeiro.
   Paul Claudel was Ambassador for French Affairs in Brazil at the time.

   Amidst this luxuriant nature, which he felt to be hostile and
   incongruous in the divine plan, Claudel takes stock of his life as he
   approaches fifty. He revisits his fundamentals: his conversion, the
   revelation of Rimbaud, the failure of his monastic vocation, the
   failure of his encounter with the “rose” on the boat to China, the
   abandonment of the child he fathered adulterously, the consent to
   marriage “there” and to “these children I had in my dreams”. But there
   is always the call of the sea, flight, exile and loneliness. The quest
   for an absolute between the poetic work and the Christian incarnation
   of the soul.

   The bitterness that runs through this work finds recourse in a love
   that binds him to God, an exhortation to the daily celebration of mass,
   which is his access to God, an exaltation of the Eucharist, experienced
   both in its intimate destitution and as a carnal, cannibal, almost
   orgasmic union, as well as in the droll and disenchanted verve of the
   gaze he brings to bear on his fellow men.
   A ritual to contain the inner disorder, a congestive, exacerbated
   Catholicism to ward off inner defeat, the temptation of the “cessation
   of everything”. A soul in crisis, calling upon a silent God, discussing
   “man to man” with Him, this Father who sends his Son and men to
   sacrifice (we are in 1917), a soul who associates a maternal and
   eroticised Virgin Mary with God the Father.

   The form of the poem is rhymed and follows the liturgical development
   of the mass known as the Pius V mass, at the beginning of the twentieth
   century, but it merges freely with the poet’s inspiration and torment,
   who dilates sequences here and there as he pleases. So, while the
   “Credo” for example remains a faithful interpretation of the confession
   of faith, the “Consecration” is substantially embellished and devotes
   most of its 85 verses to Rimbaud.
   For me, there is no adherence to a profession of faith, but to a poetic
   and theatrical work that identifies with the line in Saint John’s
   Gospel: “In the beginning was the Word”.
   Didier Sandre

   NEW PRODUCTION

   BOOKINGS OPEN IN JANUARY 2020
